<br>
Actually, can ANYONE answer that question?<br>
<br>
Our pets are not pets folks.  They are an animated DOT.  I call mine fuzzy but if you boil it down all they do is damage.  To properly balance them we need only figure out what our total DPS/useful utility should be in solo, xp group, and raid situations; take X% of that that should be our damage and make sure the pet is doing the remaining Y%.  How the damage that Y% compares to a magician or necromancers pet doesn't matter except as a point of curiosity.<br>
<br>
Personally I would expect, in all three situations that a beastlord should slightly outdamage a ranger since our AC is even lighter &amp; that's the way EQ typically works for the non monks <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Since we have a pet there are really 6 scenarios: solo w/pet, solo wo/pet, XP w/pet, XP wo/pet, raid w/pet, and raid wo/pet.  WITH a pet we should be able to outdamage a ranger at all levels by just a bit IMO.  Without a pet we should probably be between knights and warriors.  The only way I know of to do that is to leave our pets alone and give us a DA cap that allows us to do the extra damage ourselves.<br>
<br>
Basically I think our pets are fine once the patch goes in to make them monks instead of beastlords.  The remaining damage adjustments should come through a carefully tested DA for the beastlord class.  Skill cap should be set to whatever number gives the necessary damage adjustment though I'd expect 100-150 is where that number will be found.<br>
<br>
