<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   &quot;Which of the non-epic pets is the best in offensive melee without special attacks?&quot;</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
To help me determine the answer to that I researched the max hit, delay, swings per round, etc and came up with some interesting information.<br>
<br>
Before I get to the number, I would like to explain them a bit. These numbers are calculated DPS results, not parsed DPS. They assume that the pet / warder is using their best weapon skill and are placed behind the mob for best effect. Further, they do not take into account any special attacks, procs, bash, etc. They are calcuated based on 50% hit rate, max personal haste per level, and and average of 65% of max damage per hit.<br>
<br>
I have listed the Beastlord, three times to show the progression of Beastlord efficiency based on recent changes. Beastlord - Orig is the original Beastlord warder, assuming haste cap removal and corrected H2H cap. Beastlord - Old is the Beastlord warder post haste cap removal, but equipped with weapons. Beastlord is the current Beastlord warder<br>
<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre>   
Class       Level 9    16    25    30    40    49    54    58    60
Beastlord - Orig  2     6    11    14    30    53    56    57    63
Beastlord - Old   2     6     9    13    27    47    50    50    56
Beastlord         2     4     8    10    21    30    34    37    44
Enchanter         3     4     6    11    23    35    36    50    50
Magician          2     6    11    14    27    44    50    51    60
Necromancer       3     6    12    15    33    47    49    52    59
Shadow Knight     2     3     6     9    14    26    26    26    26
Shaman                        6     9    16    30    30    32    32
</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Leaving the Beastlord class aside for a moment, we see that the Necromancer pet is actaully the best, offensively until level 60, where the Magician water pet takes the title, though it is very close. Further, we see that the Enchanter animation is in a fairly respectible position, the Shaman spirit wolf at best is sitting somewhere around the level 49 Mage pet, while the Shadow Knight brings up the rear, clocking in around the level 40 Mage pet.<br>
<br>
Now, to the Beastlords. The original Beastlord warder, running at maximum haste, and with weapon skills corrected, was capable of putting out just above the level 60 Mage pet after the Mage/Necro damage upgrade. At the time, Beastlord warders were capped at 55 max hit, had a 24 delay, and were quadding. Unfortunately, these numbers were unachievable as Beastlord warders were using H2H attacks which were capped as a Warrior at 100. Consequently, Beastlords were seeing roughly 1/3rd of this.<br>
<br>
When the haste cap was removed, VI also implemented a change which allowed all pets to wield weapons, this is what allowed Beastlords to determine the cause of their warder's low DPS. As we can see, the Beastlord warder lost potentially 7 DPS at the top end when VI made this change. The reason for this drop was because warders were moved to the same base delay as all other non-mage pets at 27 vice 24. Most Beastlord's didn't really notice the difference because their warders were hitting for far more overall DPS due to the weapons bug. VI admitted that this was a bug, but they left the bug in until they could adjust our warders to roughly this level of damage output.<br>
<br>
Before the recent patch VI state that their goal was to make the Beastlord warder do roughly the same damage, as they were with weapons. Many Beastlords felt this would be acceptable and were looking forwarder to getting back up near Mages and Necros, unfortunately something went very wrong.<br>
<br>
With the recent patch, VI, put Beastlord warders back at 24 delay, but upgraded their max hit to 69, vice 70 for the Mage earth pet and 68 for the Mage water/air pets. The potential was there for Beastlord warders to exceed even the Mage epic pet and clocking in at an amazing 78 DPS. But something went horribly wrong. It is suspected that the intent was to make Beastlord warders into Monks, instead they were made into Beastlords themselves and suffered up to a 12 DPS drop in efficiency because of it, which placed them squarely at the level 49 Mage pet.<br>
<br>
